{"title":"Graspness Discovery in Clutters for Fast and Accurate Grasp Detection","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"6-DoF grasp detection in cluttered scenes wastes computation and reduces accuracy by uniformly sampling candidate grasp points and ignoring where to grasp.","method":"Define a geometry-driven quality, graspness, that scores point locations and approach directions by a look-ahead search. For each point and sampled view, generate grasp candidates via grid sampling over in-plane rotations and approach depths, score them with an analytic force model (Dex-Net) and filter by a threshold; extend to scenes by reconstructing the scene and performing collision checking before projecting and normalizing scores to obtain point-wise and view-wise scene-level graspness. This produces an object-agnostic ‘graspable landscape’ that concentrates sampling on highly graspable regions."},{"problem":"Direct look-ahead search to compute graspness is too slow for practical use; a fast, general module is needed to predict graspable regions and views in single-view point clouds.","method":"Propose a Cascaded Graspness Model (CGM): a sparse-convolution ResUNet14 backbone extracts point features; an MLP predicts point-wise graspness and objectness to select seed points via thresholding and farthest-point sampling; a second MLP predicts view-wise graspness for each seed. During training, probabilistic view selection samples views proportional to predicted graspness. CGM is transferable across objects, viewpoints, and sensors, and serves as a plug-and-play sampler that boosts accuracy and speed of existing methods (e.g., GPD, PointNetGPD, and GraspNet baselines) while running at ~0.1s per scene."},{"problem":"End-to-end 6-DoF grasp detection needs to be both accurate and efficient by focusing computation on promising regions and views.","method":"Introduce GSNet, a two-stage network that integrates CGM for early filtering and a Grasp Operation Model (GOM) for grasp generation. GSNet groups points in directional cylinder spaces around each selected seed point–view pair, aggregates features with a shared PointNet, and predicts grasp scores and gripper widths over discretized in-plane rotations and approach depths, selecting the best-scoring combination. Trained with a multi-task loss over objectness, point/view graspness, scores, and widths, GSNet achieves large AP gains (30+ AP over prior art on GraspNet-1Billion) while maintaining high inference speed."}]}
